Introduction

This notebook is part of the descriptive exploratory analyses made by the team. Here, we will compare China, where the virus has spread, with the other countries where the virus has reached. Therefore, it will be also a comparative analysis. The main purpose of which is to examine the differences in the spread of the disease in China and other parts of the world and provide recommendations to people and health practitioners based on the behavior of the disease. The project is updated as of March 11.

We are interested in 5 variables: date, number of infected, fatalities and cured in a given region, and whether the region under study belongs in China. The number of rows in the database increases with time. Due to the fact that we have only three quantitative variables, the analysis cannot be wide. The use of multivariate analysis methods doesnt make sense because of the insufficient number of variables that are strongly related to each other, which can show incorrect regularities. The data encourage the analysis of time series, which will allow us to look at the studied phenomenon not only in a point-like manner.

We study and compare the number of people infected within China and to the other countries. The number of confirmed cases in China is very high and escalating in fast pace with at almost 17 times in a week compared to the number of confirmed cases in other countries. One factor of the sudden increase, however, is the delay of data or confirmation.

In other countries outside China, we can also observe an upward trend of number of confirmed cases, similar to that in China, from the last week of February. Several factors can be observed in this behavior:

  1. The 14-day incubation period of COVID-19 is more than enough time for an infected person to spread the virus since he or she is a carrier from day 1.
  2. Lack of accessibility for testing
  3. Population density
  4. Median Age as older people are more susceptible to the disease1

1 https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/coronavirus-age-sex-demographics/

On January in China, the trend is constant - about 30 people need to be added to the sum of this tragic balance every day, but since 4th February trend is much faster (the number of victims tripled in 8 days). So while China has already developed containment measures, other countries have just started to do the same. It is all in a matter of time.

Here we are going to start to calculate the indicators to show the whole specifics of the COVID-19 Pandemic as absolute information is not enough. Mortality rate is one indicator that shows the ratio of people who died, due to the virus, to all infected. Throughout the history of the virus to date, this ratio is between 2% and 4% in China. From January 31, we can compare the ratio to the other countries because then, the first fatality was recorded outside of China. Initially, the mortality rate increased, but it began to decrease over time and never exceeded 1% until February 20. After that, mortality rate continued to increase exponentially up to 2.7% as of March 10 due to the start of the outbreak in Italy, Korea, and Iran. It is worth bearing in mind that the victims are usually an elderly person or with other diseases, so this value cannot be treated as the probability of death of a newly infected person.

EDA - Part II: Evolution Analysis of COVID-19

In the first part, we were able to compare the indicators between China and other countries. Now, let us examine the aggregated features and rank the spread of the virus per country.

2.1. Inspect the dataframe using an interactive data table feature

PRINT_MODE = 'datatable'
print_df <- function(df_in) {
  if (PRINT_MODE == 'datatable') {
    return(datatable(df_in))
  }
  return(df_in)
}

df_covid <- read_csv(str_c('covid_19_data.csv'))
colnames(df_covid) <- make.names(colnames(df_covid))
df_covid %>% print_df()

In the next sections, we will take different insights by studying the evolution of the COVID19 in different perspectives of view, following a top-bottom approach. So, we will start from the most aggregated features before understanting the specific variables.

2.2. Visualization of Aggregated Indicators

correct_year <- function(date_in) {
    if (nchar(str_split(date_in, "/")[[1]][[3]]) == 2) {
        return(str_c(date_in, '20'))
    }
    date_in
}

df_covid$ObservationDate <- sapply(df_covid$ObservationDate, correct_year)

df_covid <- df_covid %>% 
    mutate(ObservationDate = as.Date(ObservationDate, '%m/%d/%Y'))

df_covid_time_aggregate <- df_covid %>% 
  group_by(ObservationDate) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(Confirmed, Deaths, Recovered), sum) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c('Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered'), 
               names_to = 'Feature', values_to = 'Value')

df_covid_time_aggregate %>% print_df()

The long form shows all different values in the same column aggregated by countries and regions. The kind of value will be determined in the ???Feature??? column, which works as a ???metadata??? feature of the table.

Now we plot the aggregated variables:

ggplot(df_covid_time_aggregate,

2.3. COVID-19 Rank per Country

We will rank the countries by the places where the most recent number of confirmed cases are larger. We will append the ranking numbers before the names of the countries:

df_covid_max_count <- df_covid %>% 
  group_by(Country.Region) %>%

df_covid_max_count$Ranking <- str_pad(as.character(1:nrow(df_covid_max_count)), 2, pad = '0')

df_rank_countries$ObservationDate <- NULL

df_covid_countries_evolution <- df_covid %>% 
  group_by(ObservationDate, Country.Region) %>%

  inner_join(df_rank_countries, by = c('Country.Region' = 'Country.Region'))

Outside China, the countries Italy, South Korea, and Iran are the top countries with high confirmed cases.

Cases have spread across Italy???s north and down to Rome, leading to a lockdown of the entire country. Iran???s capital, where leaders dismissed the virus just two weeks ago, has seen thousands infected. And cases continue to surge across Europe.

With more than 15,000 confirmed cases, Italy has reported the largest outbreak outside of China. Italian authorities first put restrictions in place in the northern region of Lombardy, where the outbreak first accelerated, before moving on Monday to restrict the movement and end public gatherings for all 60 million citizens in the country. At least 1,000 people have died because of the virus.

In Iran, two weeks ago, Iran???s leaders denied the coronavirus epidemic would be a problem. Now, with the total number of cases standing at more than 10,000, and with more than 400 people dead, Iran is scrambling to control one of the worst outbreaks in the world. The authorities failed to take protective measures at this early stage. But the problem became impossible to ignore after nearly three dozen Iranian government officials and members of parliament were infected, and a senior adviser to the supreme leader died.

The outbreaks are not all heading in the same direction. South Korea has managed to slow growth of new cases for now, through intensive testing and monitoring of infections. Italy, Iran and the United States are still reporting large numbers of new cases every day.

2.4. Mortality Rate per Country and Bernoulli Hypothesis Tests

In this section, we will use the information we have to estimate the probability of fatality after getting infected with its respective standard deviation for each country and for all the world.

To do that, we will apply a Bernoullis Hypothesis Test: if we want to estimate the probability of an event to occur in a population, then, by the central limit theorem, its mean is the percentage of occurrences and its standard deviation can be estimated by the expression \(\sqrt{\frac{p_0.(1-p_0)}{N}}\), where \(N\) is the number of samples. So, its normal to find bigger intervals for countries where we have not observed many infections.

This can be visually represented in a plot with error bars:

df_covid

last_date <- max(df_covid$ObservationDate)
df_covid_last <- df_covid %>% 
  filter(ObservationDate == last_date) %>%
  group_by(Country.Region) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars('Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered'), sum) %>% 
  filter(Deaths > 0) %>% 
  mutate(Mortality = Deaths / Confirmed) %>% 
  mutate(Std = sqrt((Mortality * (1 - Mortality)) / sqrt(Confirmed)))

df_covid_last %>% print_df()

Shown above is an interactive dataframe of countries with COVID cases and their corresponding mortality rates.

We have approximately \(95 \%\) of probability inside a centered interval with a width of \(\pm 2\) standard deviations:

Intervals - Gaussian

df_covid_last_filtered <- df_covid_last %>% filter(Confirmed > 100)
mean_mortality <- sum(df_covid_last_filtered$Deaths) / sum(df_covid_last_filtered$Confirmed)

ggplot(df_covid_last_filtered, 
       aes(x = reorder(Country.Region, Mortality), fill = Country.Region)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean_mortality, linetype = 'dashed', color = 'red') +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mortality - 2 * Std, ymax = Mortality + 2 * Std)) +
  geom_point(aes(y = Mortality), size = 10, color = 'black', shape=21) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 18), legend.position = 'none') +
  xlab('Country') + coord_flip() +
  ggtitle('Mortality Rate') + labs(subtitle = 'Hypothesis Test at 90% of Significance')

All the error bars overlap with the red line that represents the mean mortality when counting all the countries, except for the South Korea and Germany, that seems to present a smaller number of deaths. Also, the mean is near of the values found for Italy and China, which makes sense since they have the biggest numbers of infections (1st and 3rd places respectively).

The South Korea is the fourth country in the infections number ranking and has a smaller mortality rate. It???s interesting and maybe it???s an indication of an excellent health care system or something related to the average age of the population.

Summary of Initial Conclusions

  1. The number of infected is much higher in China than in other parts of the world,

  2. The number of people cured of the virus is growing at a rapid, nonlinear rate,

  3. Mortality is at slow pace in China but at rapid growth in other countries at more than 3%. Other countries should be able to identify, isolate and care for patients early, including providing optimized care for infected patients.

  4. Lack of accessibility to testing is one of the problems why countries could not react fast against the virus.

  5. In China, the share of cured people initially dropped, but from 27 January it has been growing rapidly,

  6. The number of cured is relatively increasing at each fatality, and

  7. China is healing as it is already got its stimulus plan lined up. It applies a hybrid model which seems to be effective: lockdown clusters of the virus and rapid testing in all remote areas.
